The Negative Directional Indicator (-DI) measures the presence of a <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="1" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/d/downtrend.asp">downtrend </a>and is part of the <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="2" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/a/adx.asp">Average Directional Index</a> (ADX). If -DI is sloping upward, it's a sign that the price downtrend is getting stronger. This indicator is nearly always plotted along with the <a class="pseudoStyle" data-component="link" data-ordinal="3" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/p/positivedirectionalindicator.asp">Positive Directional Indicator</a> (+DI).

